#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:47
msgid ""
"In other words, each entry ``out[i,j,...,:]`` is an N-dimensional value "
"drawn from the distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:59
msgid ":obj:`random.Generator.multivariate_normal`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:60
msgid "which should be used for new code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:64
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:65
msgid ""
"The mean is a coordinate in N-dimensional space, which represents the "
"location where samples are most likely to be generated.  This is analogous "
"to the peak of the bell curve for the one-dimensional or univariate normal "
"distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:70
msgid ""
"Covariance indicates the level to which two variables vary together. From "
"the multivariate normal distribution, we draw N-dimensional samples, :math:"
"`X = [x_1, x_2, ... x_N]`.  The covariance matrix element :math:`C_{ij}` is "
"the covariance of :math:`x_i` and :math:`x_j`. The element :math:`C_{ii}` is "
"the variance of :math:`x_i` (i.e. its \"spread\")."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:77
msgid ""
"Instead of specifying the full covariance matrix, popular approximations "
"include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:80
msgid "Spherical covariance (`cov` is a multiple of the identity matrix)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:81
msgid ""
"Diagonal covariance (`cov` has non-negative elements, and only on the "
"diagonal)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:84
msgid ""
"This geometrical property can be seen in two dimensions by plotting "
"generated data-points:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:90
msgid ""
"Diagonal covariance means that the variables are independent, and the "
"probability density contours have their axes aligned with the coordinate "
"axes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/random/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.random.RandomState.multivariate_normal:99
msgid ""
"Note that the covariance matrix must be positive semidefinite (a.k.a. "
"nonnegative-definite). Otherwise, the behavior of this method is undefined "
"and backwards compatibility is not guaranteed."
msgstr ""

